node.text:
GLUTE WORKOUT + A DOSE OF EDUCATION 🍑🍑🍑🤓

Please make sure to SAVE it really helps my content keep popping up in the IG feed.🙏🏼🙏🏼🥺❤️

I know there are a lot of workouts floating around instagram but I do hope you read my captions when I go into more details on exercises. This will help you actually LEARN more about what you are doing.💪🏼✨

A1) LEG PRESS FEET HIGH 3x 10 as 1 & 1/4 rep. Feet high is targeting your glutes in their lengthened position. The quarter is added into the bottom where your glutes are under the most amount of tension. Remember to keep yourself pulled down into the sear & no rounding of back.

A2) BACK EXTENSION 3x 10 weighted + 10 body weight. Holding the weight out higher in front of you as opposed to close on your chest will make this exercise harder.

B1) HIGH STEP UP 3x 10. Focus on the front leg on the box doing all the work and the back leg as little as possible. I hinge over at the hips to increase the stretch in the glute.

B2) SINGLE LEG HIP THRUST 3x 12 as 1 & 1/4. One of the most savage body weight only exercises.

C1) BACK FOOT ELEVATED RDL 3x 10. Single leg exercise however the back leg is up on the bench for support. I like to do these with a slower tempo to increase TUT.

C2) CABLE KICBACK 1 & 1/4 3x 10.
C3) CABLE STRAIGHT LEG ABDUCTION 3X 10 as 1 & 1/4.

This was an exact workout of mine prelockdown.💪🏼❤️
Let me know what you think if you give this a go.

node.text:
STOP OBSESSING OVER CALORIES BURNED ON YOUR FITNESS TRACKERS‼️

❌Please do not base what you eat around  the calories burned on your watch.
❌Please do not look think you need to eat back calories burned.

There have been many studies to show that activity trackers are NOT consistently accurate/reliable as a measure of energy expenditure.

I know so many of you out there rely on these numbers to justify whether your workout was good or not…whether it was effective…and often feel like it was a waste of time or a failure if a certain number on your watch wasn’t hit.

1) Burning a number of calories shouldn’t be your #1 goal of a workout.
2) As a coach that number doesn’t impact the programming in the gym.

I wear an activity tracker (FitBit) but the only thing I use it for are steps and sleep.

Fitness trackers are highly inaccurate and all fitness trackers would give you different numbers. They simply don’t have enough accurate data about you to make an informed reading. ⚠️

Simply doing a workout to burn a number of calories is not a good mindset to have long term and it takes the enjoyment out of this lifestyle.

There are far better ways to track during out workouts such as the weight used in the gym for your lifts, improvements in technique, how exercise makes you feel, the mental health benefits etc. Track your progress to get stronger!💪🏼💪🏼💪🏼👏🏼

REMEMBER: THESE INACCURATE NUMBERS SHOULDN’T MAKE YOU FEEL BAD ABOUT A WORKOUT!✨

HOW TO: SPLIT SQUAT ❌✅🔥🔥front & side view.

SAVE + RESHARE if it was helpful !🙏🏼 

Split squats are a staple in both mine & my client programs. It’s a love/hate relationship for me. 🥵There are many variations, even by adding elevation for front foot, back foot etc it can recruit muscles in different ways. You can do them body weight only, hold dumbbells, a barbell, plus incorporate different methods like pauses, 1 & 1/4 reps etc to ramp up the intensity.🔥👊🏼

🎯The goal here is to drive that front knee forward to maximise knee flexion. This also makes it a more quad dominant exercise. Yes it is okay for your knee to travel past your toes! 👏🏼👏🏼
 Don’t let your knee cave in! This is very common & often why lunges/split squats can result in knee pain. Make sure to turn your toes out slightly and keep your knee tracking out in line with it.

‼️Here are some brief coaching cues to think about when doing this exercise:

Drop back knee down toward the floor.
Push front knee forwards.
Front foot should be turned out slightly.
Knee tracks in line with toes - Don’t let knee cave in!!!
Think ‘hamstring to calf’ when travelling forward.
Front foot should be flat to floor.
Back leg heel up.
Core braced.
Shoulders back/upright torso.

I hope this helps! 🤓❤️
@laurensimpsonfitness

node.text:
What are your non-negotiables for this week? 💕🌈🌻

Whenever I want to get back on track or be really focused on a goal (whether it be shredding, building, or just maintaining) the secret lies within getting MOMENTUM.

✨Take each day as it comes.✨

Here is the current list I make myself every morning - that I then reflect on everything night.

🍎Stick to my meal plan
👟Step goal: 12,000 minimum
💪🏼Workout
💧2L+ water
🎧1 podcast min
😴6.5hours min sleep

The more good days you have - you get on a roll. The days accumulate. There is a huge sense of satisfaction with ticking off things you achieve that helps with building good habits.

Now let’s be real…that first week is always tough. You may feel hungry, you may feel sore, you may feel a little more tired than usual…BUT every day TICK OFF that list. You’ll see me at night time checking off my list to keep me accountable.

If you had a sh*tty week last week I encourage you to just focusing on each day ahead right now. Start with small changes and build momentum.

SO, WRITE IT DOWN AND TICK IT OFF THIS WEEK QUEENS! ✍🏻✨🌈

COMMON DEADLIFT MISTAKES ❌⚠️🆘

Please SAVE & RESHARE if this was helpful 🙏🏼

Here are a few deadlift mistakes I commonly see as a coach.

⚠️ HYPEREXTENDING THE LOCKOUT 
You do not need to excessively thrust forward & lean back to lockout your deadlift.

Butt squeeze here isn’t building your glutes girls! Your glutes are actually under zero tension at the top - if anything you are just engaging your lower back which is not want you want here!

✅ Just stand up straight. Neutral spine and hips in extension. Slight glute squeeze is fine - just don’t overdo it.

⚠️ BAR STARTING TO FAR AWAY.
When you are starting with your feet too far away from the bar this actually makes deadlifting harder due to the bar path (increases horizontal moment arm). This can also put pressure on your spine. 🥴

✅ Make sure you start with the bar right up at your shins. The bar should remain close to your body right from the start. Bar path should be straight up and down. 

🥵 ROUNDING THE UPPER BACK
It’s common to see upper back rounding as a result of zero tension being created with your shoulder blades and lats. There is no tightness. When your upper back begins to round, tension moves away from your glutes/hammies to back.

✅From the starting position keep your shoulder blades pulled back and down. Your lats should be engaged, bar pulled tight in toward your body. Spine should be kept neutral.

⚠️NO RESET, USING MOMENTUM & FORM BREAKING DOWN.

Now ‘touch and go’ reps are not bad however I do recommend to slow down your reps and reset at the bottom of every rep if your goal is to continue working on your form and build strength.

✅Resetting each rep can make sure your body has max tension (eg resetting upper back tension), your form isn’t breaking down, and every rep is pulled from a solid foundation. It’s also better for building up strength out of the bottom as you are pulling from a complete stop - you aren’t relying on the ‘bouncing’.

I hope this video helped. Let me know ❤️

node.text:
My goal was always to become the ‘thinnest’ version of me. 🥵 I thought the leaner I was - the more successful I would be, the more popular I would become and the more I would look like a ‘fitness’ girl. 

I was so uneducated. I was 10kg lighter on the left than I am now, I severly restricted my calories for a prolonged time, I was nutrient deprived, and overtrained. 😔

This came at a consequence. My very very low body fat levels + extremely high stresses on my body due to under eating and overtraining meant I lost my period - for years.

My body was barely functioning for my day to day activity - let alone sitting at optimal reproductive health levels. I was also moody, cold 24/7, hair loss, constant headaches, digestive issues, insomnia and my hormones were so out of whack.

At my lowest points it was also a time when my insecurities were at an all time high.

It took me shifting my mindset to allow myself to gain weight, take a step back from exercise like I was and provide it with the nutrients it needed to thrive. My body needed a lot of love. I had to trust the process and just keep on going and growing.🦋🦋🦋🦋

Now everyone is different but this is just a little on my journey. Please seek professional advice.

Sitting at an extremely low body fat % is not healthy for females. The ‘quick fix’ often comes with a price long term to your body. It’s not worth sacrificing your health and happiness.

Super shredded abs don’t define you or your happiness. Nor does chasing the lowest body fat % you can.

NOURISH OVER PUNISH.👏🏼👏🏼👏🏼👏🏼👏🏼

BUILD YOUR SHOULDERS 💪🏼🔥🔥

It’s no secret I love training shoulders. I have been known to have pretty ‘jacked’ shoulders over the years according to Mark.🤣🤣

If you do want to grow your shoulders, your exercise selection matters. You will need to include exercises that hit each head - front, medial, rear delt - for that well balanced ‘capped’ look. 👏🏼 

Here are example exercises for front, middle & rear.

1️⃣FRONT (ANTERIOR)  DELTS
65 degree incline press

Keep your elbows in front of your body (not flared out too much)
Neutral grip
65 degree Incline allows for a better positioning with your body 
This will also hit a little chest - which as someone who doesn’t train any direct chest, I quite like.

2️⃣MEDIAL DELTS
Lateral raise

Your arm path should be slighting out in front for lateral raises. Don’t take your arms directly out to the sides of your body which is a common mistake I see. This isn’t hitting your medial delt muscle optimally.

I also really like doing a cable lean away variation. I find this position takes out traps and also makes the exercise harder due to the angle/gravity.

3️⃣REAR DELTS
Rear delt flye machine

Remember with this exercise, more range of motion is not best! Once your rear delt muscle has fully contracted - anything past this is just going to engage your upper back.

Take your arms out directly to the sides & stay within your rear delts active range. 

I like the rear delt machine or cable rear delt rows.

I hope this helped 💪🏼💪🏼 let me know! @laurensimpsonfitness

QUADS WORKOUT 🔥 And bringing you a little dose of education.🤓

Hit SAVE and give this a go. 🔥

This workout is definitely a go-to of mine for quads (pre-lockdown lifting 😢)

🤎Leg extension 3x 12-15. I love using leg extension as a pre-exhaust method and just to get the blood pumping to that area. Leg extension is hitting your quads in the shortened position. The most amount of tension on your quads is at the top range.

🤎Hack squat 4x 12. My favourite machine quad building exercise. You can train your quads well without loading your spine as much as a barbell squat.

🤎Alternating forward step lunge 3x 12.
Here I am taking a smaller step forward and due to the forward motion of the concentric it requires a lot more power out of the front leg to push back to the starting position. “Catch the weight” and control as you push back. The smaller stride puts more emphasis on quads.

🤎Leg press low and narrow 3x 15. When your feet are lower on the platform there is greater knee flexion in the bottom position so it means your quads need to do work work! 

🤎 Single leg extension 3x 12. I really like unilateral work for quads - really focus on isolating the muscle.

🤎 Heels elevated goblet squat 3x 15. Heels are on a big elevation to help with pushing knees forward. More knee flexion = more quad recruitment. Higher rep no lockout at top.

Like the way that I train?? 💕✨

Be selective about how you spend your time and who you spend your time with.

It’s a sign of self respect and self love.

Surround yourself with those who make you feel good enough, love all of you - not just part of you, who don’t make you question who you are, who uplift you and support you. Those are your people.🌻🌈

(Ps Definitely not coming out of lockdown looking like this. 😂😅I will be visiting the salon ASAP! @sarahjadehair )

ROMANIAN DEADLIFT VARIATIONS 💪🏼🔥

PLEASE SAVE + RESHARE.✌🏼

Recently I did a post about different deadlift variations and I wanted to break it down further by focusing on Romanian deadlifts as these are ones I get asked frequently about. 🙏🏼

The cues for RDL are going to be pretty similar across these variations.

👉🏼Neutral spine
👉🏼Slight bend in knees
👉🏼Keep shins relatively vertical
👉🏼Hinge over at the hips and push your butt back
👉🏼Key is to maximise hip flexion

💥HIP BANDED RDL💥
-Band set at hip height
-Torso on a slight lean with tension against band
-Bar path is further away from the body in comparison
-Long band provides resistance throughout the exercise
🍑Bottom range of RDL = glutes in the lengthened position
🍑Top range of the RDL with edition of band = glutes in the shortened position

I learned this one from @coach_kassem @coachmarkcarroll 

💥TRAP BAR RDL💥
-Allows for a neutral/wider grip
-More natural position for your body to lift and brace
-This is one of my favourite RDL variations as I do like the neutral grip. 

💥B-STANCE RDL💥
-Staggered stance
-Single leg variation
-Back leg is there for stability
-Non working leg’s toes should be brought back to be in line with your working leg heel.
-Lift heel on the back leg.
-You can lift heavier on b-stance than a true single leg variation given the extra stability. 

💥DUMBBELL RDL💥
-Great option for beginner to learn hip hinge pattern
-For heavier dumbbells use wrist straps so grip strength isn’t a limiting factor
-Keep tightness in upper back to avoid rounding
-Keep within active range - don’t go too slow.

I hope this post was helpful!
❤️❤️ let me know!

 @laurensimpsonfitness
